description.narrative: By 2023, service providers have strengthened capacity to provide quality and integrated chid survival and development, learning and child protection services., which contributes to Cross-Sectoral - Social And Behaviour Change, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Safe And Equitable Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Services And Practices, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Water, Sanitation And Hygiene Systems And Empowerment Of Communities. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: All Namibian children from ages 0â€“10 years have improved access to quality and equitable maternal, neonatal and child health, education, child protection, Early Child Development (ECD), civil registration, nutrition and Water, Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH) services by 2023.

description.narrative: Through evidence-based advocacy, UNICEF contributed to prioritization of strategic actions for Nutrition, ECD and Sanitation in the national Harambee Prosperity Plan 2021-2025. Furthermore, UNICEF-supported community-led total sanitation (CLTS) approach was adopted as a critical component of the efforts to eliminate open defecation by the Ministry of Urban and Rural Development. A Health Sector Procurement for Impact analysis supported by UNICEF is informing revisions to the Procurement Act to improve efficiency and transparency, and establishment of a joint Reference Group between the key sectors to oversee implementation of recommendations and allow for continuous dialogue to address procurement bottlenecks.;; | Status:Partially met | As-of Date:01/12/2021
